<LENGTH>
<P>
659 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
ON AGING: PROGRAMS FOR OLDER JOB-SEEKERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By the UCLA/USC Long-Term Care Gerontology Center 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Many older job-seekers are professionals who face difficulty in their search. 
Labor Department data from 1988 show that more than 25% of employed workers 
over age 55 hold managerial and professional positions. And nearly one-third of 
the 3,600 older job-seekers who called the Job Hotline of the Los Angeles 
Council on Careers for Older Americans in 1988 were in managerial or 
professional positions. An estimated 600,000 mid-level white-collar positions 
were eliminated in the United States by exit incentives between 1980 and 1986, 
and an additional 400,000 will be eliminated by 1990. 
</P>
<P>
The older professional job-seeker faces three major barriers. First, few 
programs are designed to assist the mature professional, and limited government 
funds are designated to help this population re-enter the work force. Business 
outplacement programs are generally reserved for high-level executives, not 
mid-managers or professionals. 
</P>
<P>
Second, age discrimination can be a greater barrier for the older professional 
than for the lower-skilled job-seeker, because employers view older 
professionals as more expensive human-resource investments. 
</P>
<P>
Third, many people, including older professionals themselves, believe that 
people who have made "career progress," even modestly climbing the corporate 
ladder, should be able to handle the job search alone. However, most 
professionals need help marketing their skills, developing a network of people 
with common interests, and learning the tricks, such as how to summarize 30 
years of employment on a one-page resume. 
</P>
<P>
Some nonprofit and for-profit organizations, particularly in larger urban 
areas, have begun to recognize this need and develop programs to assist older 
professionals. Some are described in responses to the questions that follow. 
</P>
<P>
Question: Six months ago, I took early retirement from my position as vice 
president of public relations with a major bank. I am an energetic, 60-year-old 
woman who wants to work. I have sent out more than 100 resumes but have 
received very few responses -- three interviews and no job offers. What help is 
available? 
</P>
<P>
Answer: Eight coordinating councils operate model older-worker programs 
throughout the country. Six of these (in Boston; Chicago; Detroit; Lincoln, 
Neb.; Los Angeles and New York City) have programs designed specifically for 
managers or professionals. 
</P>
<P>
Most of these councils offer intensive three- or four-day job-search seminars 
focusing on skills assessment, interview practice, resume development, 
networking and generating leads. Several programs offer extensive follow-up 
activities, including staff contacts with program participants each week. 
Placement results have been exceptional: Project ABLE of Detroit reports a 75% 
placement rate and Boston ABLE a 60% placement rate. 
</P>
<P>
According to Denise Jessup of the Los Angeles Council on Careers for Older 
Americans, "Older professionals have special needs in the job search. These 
programs have been designed with the recognition that older job-seekers face a 
great deal of rejection. Feeling positive about your skills and what you can 
offer an employer is the first step toward capturing a new job." Write the Los 
Angeles Council on Careers for Older Americans, 5225 Wilshire Blvd., Suite 204, 
Los Angeles 90036, for information about the nearest coordinating council. 
</P>
<P>
Other nonprofit organizations also attempt to meet the needs of older 
professionals. Nationwide, there are 16 independent Forty Plus organizations. 
These groups have a self-help focus; their main function is to help members 
help themselves get jobs. There is usually no paid staff; volunteer work is 
required of members, who generally pay an initial membership and monthly fee. 
Telephones, desks, word processors, support groups, job-search seminars, want 
ads and other publications are available. To locate the Forty Plus nearest you, 
look in your local phone book or call the Los Angeles chapter at (213) 
388-2301. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA091089-0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 105264 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
September 10, 1989, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
View; Part 6; Page 8; Column 1; View Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
390 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
ERMA BOMBECK: ALL SHE NEEDS IS A SPORTING CHANCE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Erma Bombeck 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Throughout the years I have eliminated from my life one sport after another. It 
began with skiing, when I didn't see the wisdom of pursuing any type of 
recreation where an ambulance was parked at the bottom of the hill. 
Synchronized swimming didn't do it for me either, as my best feature is my nose 
and I don't necessarily need a nose plug attached to it. 
</P>
<P>
I discovered tennis to be a sport that attracted people you couldn't trust. One 
minute, they smiled when your serve tipped the net and shouted, "Take two." The 
next, they purposely slammed a ball into the opposite side from where you were 
standing waiting for it. 
</P>
<P>
People who hop on a luge and bounce along out of control at 80 m.p.h. on a 
sheet of ice are just real strange. And besides, my stomach sticks out . . . 
even when I lie on my back. 
</P>
<P>
You may now add rock climbing to my list. I remember the first time I saw a 
rock climber on television. He weighed about 38 pounds and for no reason began 
to scale a perfectly vertical slab of rock. If I had Velcro hands and Robert 
Redford was hosting an Amway party at the top, you couldn't have gotten me to 
do that. 
</P>
<P>
You can imagine my surprise when I read a story the other day that said 
climbers are now using artificial walls to "eliminate environmental damage." 
</P>
<P>
I care about this planet as much as the next person, but how many people do you 
know who go out on Sunday and hang onto a piece of rock with their fingernails? 
Five? Ten? Twenty? Are we talking crowds here? 
</P>
<P>
There couldn't be more than a handful with that kind of guts, and that doesn't 
exactly add up to rock gridlock. 
</P>
<P>
There are fears that go with every sport -- fear of having your bowling ball 
bounce into the next lane . . . fear of knocking your tennis ball into the club 
dining room . . . fear of having a leg cramp playing Goony Golf . . . and fear 
of being the only person ever to ride a chair lift all day without getting off 
once. 
</P>
<P>
But rock climbing! I didn't figure on being afraid I'd destroy the environment. 
I would prefer to wonder what would happen if you reached for a little "bolt" 
to hang onto the rock and it turned out to be a snake's head. I'm sorry, but I 
want a sport where I can show my broken nail to someone without having it be my 
last words. As for adventure -- appearing in aerobics in a yellow leotard is as 
crazy as I want to get. 
</P>
</TEXT>
