<TEXT>
<P>
NEWS NOTES: The syndicated TV show "Smash Hits" bows Sept. 23 with a 
sweepstakes promotion in which a viewer will win a "rock 'n' roll prize 
package." And they're not just talking about Joan Jett's key chain and Tom 
Petty's cigarette lighter. The package consists of a bass autographed by Paul 
McCartney, keyboards autographed by Elton John, a guitar signed by Jon Bon 
Jovi, and drums inscribed by Phil Collins. The winner will be announced early 
next month. The half-hour show, which will air on KNBC-TV in Los Angeles on 
Saturdays at 2:30 p.m., will be hosted by deejay Scott Shannon. 
</P>
<P>
Michael and Janet Jackson aren't the only members of that famous family with 
albums slated for release before Christmas. Jermaine is expected Oct. 3 with 
"Don't Take It Personal," Randy is due Oct. 17 with "Randy and the Gypsies," 
and Marlon weighs in Nov. 7 with "Marlon Jackson." LaToya Jackson, meanwhile, 
who bared herself earlier this year in the pages of Playboy magazine, is 
seeking to capitalize on the association. Her new album -- which has been 
released only in Europe -- features songs titled "Bad Girl" and "Playboy." 
</P>
<P>
Belinda Carlisle's upcoming album, "Runaway Horses," will contain a flyer 
promoting two charities: People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals and Earth 
Communication Office, which works to raise awareness of the Greenhouse Effect. 
. . . PolyGram Records obviously expected "Great Balls of Fire," the recent 
film biography of Jerry Lee Lewis, to be a hit. The company is releasing three 
(count 'em) double album sets titled "The Killer," collecting Lewis' work from 
1963 to 1977. Avoid the rush: Eurythmics have already filmed four videos to 
support songs from their upcoming "We Too Are One" album. . . . The upcoming 
feature film "Rising Storm" will be dedicated to Tom Donahue and other pioneers 
of free-form FM radio in the '60s. The film, due in January, concerns a 
futuristic America ruled by a dictatorial televangelist. . . . MTV nixed the 
original version of Aerosmith's "Love in an Elevator" video, which showed side 
and rear views of a topless woman, but is airing a compromise version with 
black "censored" bars over the racier scenes. 
</P>
