<HEADLINE>
<P>
ARAB GUNMEN SLAY ACTING MAYOR IN WEST BANK TOWN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
JERUSALEM 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Masked Palestinians shot and killed the Israeli-appointed deputy mayor of a 
West Bank town Saturday evening because he had defied activists' orders to 
resign. 
</P>
<P>
The masked assailants burst into the home of Deputy Mayor Yusuf Mohammed Milhem 
of Qalqiliya and shot him at least six times in the chest, Arab reports said. 
</P>
<P>
An army spokesman said Milhem, 46, was rushed to an Israeli hospital, where he 
died of his wounds. An Israeli army spokesman said police have begun an 
investigation. 
</P>
<P>
Milhem and his house had been attacked several times by activists demanding 
that he resign. In January, 1989, while he was being treated at Qalqiliya 
Hospital, masked men entered his room and stabbed him. 
</P>
<P>
Milhem's superior, the mayor of Qalqiliya, moved to a nearby Israeli town after 
he was threatened for refusing to resign. The underground leadership of the 
Palestinian uprising has repeatedly called on Israeli-appointed officials to 
leave their posts. 
</P>
<P>
After the shooting, the army ordered all the people in the area into a nearby 
field for questioning, Palestinian sources said. 
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a knife-wielding Arab passenger stabbed the Israeli driver of a bus 
and tried to force the vehicle off the road at the same site where 16 people 
were killed in a similar attack last June. 
</P>
<P>
Other passengers grabbed the attacker and the bus remained on the road, 
according to news reports. 
</P>
<P>
In the occupied territories, Palestinians brought business and transportation 
to a standstill Saturday in a general strike to mark the beginning of the 22nd 
month of the uprising against Israeli occupation. The army said Nablus, the 
West Bank's largest town, was under curfew for the eighth consecutive day as 
troops and security agents searched for uprising activists. 
</P>
<P>
An off-duty Israeli police dog handler was burned badly when a Molotov cocktail 
was thrown at his car, police said. 
</P>
<P>
Reuven Perlmutter, 28, who was driving alone, received burns over 25% of his 
body and was in serious but stable condition in an Israeli hospital. 
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio said four suspects had been detained. 
</P>
</TEXT>
