<TEXT>
<P>
The Little Red Riding Hood of today is a "real wimp" compared to the original 
heroine of ancient folk tales on which the character is based, according to UC 
Berkeley anthropologist Alan Dundes. "Male writers completely ruined the tale . 
. .," said Dundes. "They made the girl a weak little thing who had to be 
rescued. The original folk tale is a female story in which the mother sends the 
daughter out and the little girl is triumphant." What's more, he said, she 
didn't wear a hood, red or otherwise. He said the culprits who rearranged the 
tale were 17th-Century French writer Charles Perrault and, later, the Grimm 
brothers -- Jacob and Wilhelm. 
</P>
