<P>
FICTION 
</P>
<P>
TREVAYNE by Robert Ludlum (Bantam: $5.95). Former Undersecretary of State 
Andrew Trevayne is recruited to ferret out renegade employees involved in 
piecemeal selling of the government. 
</P>
<P>
PRIME TIME by Joan Collins (Pocket: $5.50). Roman a clef about an entertainer 
whose star faded and was revived. 
</P>
<P>
HERB'N'LORNA: A Love Story by Eric Kraft (Obelisk: $8.95). Peter Leroy, at his 
grandmother's funeral, learns that she and Gumpa led an affectionate and 
unconventional life selling "coarse goods." 
</P>
<P>
TO LOVE A ROGUE by Valerie Sherwood (Onyx: $4.50). During the Revolutionary War 
Lorraine London is rescued from indentured servitude by a stalwart gunrunner. 
</P>
<P>
BLOOD RUN by Leah Ruth Robinson (Onyx: $4.50). Dr. Evelyn Sutcliffe refuses to 
accept the labeling of suicide in the death of her colleague Dr. Shelley 
Reininsh who dies after being rushed to the emergency room. 
</P>
<P>
NONFICTION 
</P>
<P>
A NEW AGE NOW BEGINS: A People's History of the American Revolution, Vols. I 
and II by Page Smith (Penguin: $29.95). Part of an eight-volume set, which ends 
with the 1920s, that is scheduled to be released through 1991. It depicts the 
evolvement of 13 colonies into one entity -- America. 
</P>
<P>
HEBREW MYTHS: The Book of Genesis by Robert Graves and Raphael Patai (Anchor: 
$9.95). Scholars of ancient civilizations reproduce, interpret and analyze 61 
Judaic myths. 
</P>
<P>
MISSING BEAUTY by Teresa Carpenter (Zebra: $4.95). Investigative re-creation of 
the murder of a Boston Combat Zone prostitute by a middle-aged college 
professor. 
</P>
<P>
MEN OF ZEAL: A Candid Inside Story of the Iran-Contra Hearings by William S. 
Cohen and George J. Mitchell (Penguin: $9.95). Two senators sift through the 
evidence, hearings and findings of the Tower Commission that suggest renegade 
employees are within the government. 
</P>
<P>
SELF-HELP / REFERENCE 
</P>
<P>
ALL YOU CAN DO IS ALL YOU CAN DO: But All You Can Do Is Enough! by A. L. 
Williams (Ivy: $4.95). The author shares his "six-point approach," which helped 
elevate him from a $10,000-a-year high school coach to a multimillion-dollar 
insurance industry executive. 
</P>
<P>
THE AIRLINE PASSENGER'S GUERRILLA HANDBOOK by George Albert Brown (Blakes: 
$14.95). Brown glides us through cancellations, delays, smoking, children, 
pets, frequent-flyer programs, jet lag, escaping long lines and much more. 
</P>
